---
// v61 — Writing Room simplified per Dave (2026-06-07): only works actively
// being written live here; one uniform card per book; published companion
// works moved to the Reading Room catalog (already listed there); new
// citations/verification explainer anchors the bottom of the page.
import RoomLayout from '../../layouts/RoomLayout.astro';
---
<RoomLayout
  room="writing"
  title="Writing Room"
  subtitle="The books being written, in the open."
  width="prose"
  sourceId="writing-index"
>
  <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
    <p>
      This room holds the works the Library is actively writing. The drafts
      are real — they argue, they cite, they make their case — and they are
      openly unfinished: flagged where a source is still being verified,
      corrected in public when an error is found. Read them, and if you see
      a mistake or a sharper version of an argument, write to the
      <a href="/reference-desk/">Reference Desk</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Finished work lives elsewhere: published books and curated sources in
      the <a href="/reading/">Reading Room</a> catalog, shipped editorial
      pieces in <a href="/voices/">Voices</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The shelf has a shape. The books cover the school-trust story in three
      tenses — how the promise was built and broken (past), the fights and
      the record as they happen (present), and the repair and what it
      teaches (future) — plus the legal treatise that makes the law usable
      and, soon, editions written for particular readers: trustees,
      students, correspondents in particular states. One verified record
      underneath; many doors in.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="books mt-10" aria-labelledby="books-heading">
    <h2 id="books-heading" class="section-heading">On the desks now</h2>

    <p class="section-intro">
      Four works in progress: three books that tell the school-trust story in
      three tenses — past, present, future — and the legal treatise that
      makes the law they describe usable.
    </p>

    <article class="book-card">
      <p class="card-kicker">The past · Looking back · Draft v26</p>
      <h3 class="card-title">
        <a href="/writing/schools-of-the-republic/"><em>The Forgotten Forever Gift to Public Schools</em></a>
      </h3>
      <p class="card-byline">Margaret Bird and Dave Sullivan · A Forever Gift, Book One</p>
      <p class="card-blurb">
        How the United States built — and largely lost — a national endowment
        for public education across 235 years, followed by a portrait of the
        trust in every state.
      </p>
      <p class="card-status">Status: coauthor review under way; the notes were
        rebuilt this week onto the Library's verified-citation system, with
        three sources still flagged as open.</p>
      <div class="card-cta-row">
        <a href="/writing/schools-of-the-republic/" class="card-cta">Read on the web →</a>
        <a href="/drafts/schools-of-the-republic-latest.docx" class="card-cta">Latest draft (Word) →</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="book-card">
      <p class="card-kicker">The present · In court now</p>
      <h3 class="card-title">
        <a href="/writing/who-steals-from-children/"><em>Who Steals from Children: Volume 1 — Oregon and the Elliott</em></a>
      </h3>
      <p class="card-byline">Dave Sullivan · Reader's Edition</p>
      <p class="card-blurb">
        A first-person account of how the State of Oregon spent thirty-five
        years removing a billion-dollar working trust asset from the Common
        School Fund. The case is in court today; this volume is the evidence.
      </p>
      <p class="card-status">Status: living draft; updated as the litigation
        record grows.</p>
      <div class="card-cta-row">
        <a href="/writing/who-steals-from-children/" class="card-cta">Read on the web →</a>
        <a href="/drafts/who-steals-from-children-vol1-latest.docx" class="card-cta">Latest draft (Word) →</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="book-card">
      <p class="card-kicker">The future · Looking forward · Draft v4</p>
      <h3 class="card-title">
        <a href="/writing/stewards-of-the-republic/"><em>Stewards of the Republic</em></a>
      </h3>
      <p class="card-byline">Dave Sullivan · A Forever Gift, Book Two</p>
      <p class="card-blurb">
        Defending the forever gift in the age of artificial intelligence: what
        two centuries of school-trust failures teach the architects of the
        perpetual institutions now being chartered, and the machinery — legal,
        civic, electronic — that lets a watchful public defend a trust in
        real time.
      </p>
      <p class="card-status">Status: development draft posted with its known
        issues listed plainly on <a href="/writing/stewards-of-the-republic/">its
        page</a>; a correction pass is under way.</p>
      <div class="card-cta-row">
        <a href="/writing/stewards-of-the-republic/" class="card-cta">Read on the web →</a>
        <a href="/drafts/stewards-of-the-republic-latest.docx" class="card-cta">Latest draft (Word) →</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="book-card">
      <p class="card-kicker">Law desk · Working edition</p>
      <h3 class="card-title">
        <a href="/writing/hornbook/"><em>School Trust Lands: The Law of America's Educational Land Trusts</em></a>
      </h3>
      <p class="card-byline">America's School Trust Library · The field's first one-volume treatise</p>
      <p class="card-blurb">
        A practitioner reference for school-trust law: the granting
        instruments, the fiduciary duties, enforcement, remedies, and reform —
        twenty chapters and twenty-one state appendices.
      </p>
      <p class="card-status">Status: complete in architecture; a standing
        verification program is checking every quotation and citation against
        primary sources, with unverified items flagged on the page.</p>
      <div class="card-cta-row">
        <a href="/writing/hornbook/" class="card-cta">Open the hornbook →</a>
        <a href="/drafts/hornbook-working-edition-v1.docx" class="card-cta">Working edition (Word) →</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="essays mt-10" aria-labelledby="essays-heading">
    <h2 id="essays-heading" class="section-heading">Open essays</h2>

    <article class="essay-card">
      <h3 class="card-title">
        <a href="/writing/the-only-forever-trust/">"The Only Forever-Trust We Have Data On"</a>
      </h3>
      <p class="card-byline">Dave Sullivan · May 2026 · ~2,350 words · Working draft</p>
      <p class="card-blurb">
        Taking the school-trust failure-modes argument directly to the
        AI-governance designers building the next century's perpetual
        institutions. Comments welcome.
      </p>
    </article>

    <p class="mt-6 text-sm italic text-slate-500">
      If you'd like to be a named correspondent for a Writing Room draft — an
      early reader whose comments shape the final version — write to the
      <a href="/reference-desk/">Reference Desk</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="dispatches mt-10" aria-labelledby="dispatches-heading">
    <h2 id="dispatches-heading" class="section-heading">Dispatches — write for the Library</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
      <p>
        Seen a school-trust harm — or a win — firsthand? Send us the story
        and the documents. The Library fact-checks every dispatch against
        primary sources and publishes it at house standard: your byline, our
        verification. Recurring contributors are invited into State
        Correspondent roles.
        <a href="/writing/dispatches/">How to contribute &rarr;</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="methods mt-10" aria-labelledby="methods-heading">
    <h2 id="methods-heading" class="section-heading">Citations, footnotes, and verification</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none prose-a:text-blue-700 prose-a:underline">
      <p>
        Everything written in this room runs on one verification system. Every
        authority — every case, statute, report, and archive — lives in a
        single register that records whether we hold the original document and
        have checked our quotation and page citation against it. Where a
        citation is still being verified, the draft says so with a visible
        flag rather than passing the claim off as settled. Our own books and
        model legislation are never cited as evidence for anything.
      </p>
      <p>
        When checking finds an error, the text is corrected and the correction
        is published, not buried. This week's verification pass removed a
        famous quotation that turned out not to exist in the opinion it is
        always attributed to, corrected a billion-dollar state fund figure
        that was really a forecast, and retired a widely-repeated statistic no
        survey supports.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="/writing/how-we-check-our-work/">Read the full method — and
        what it caught — here &rarr;</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</RoomLayout>

<style>
  .section-heading {
    font-family: var(--font-serif, Georgia, serif);
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--deep-navy, #1e3a5f);
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
  }
  .book-card,
  .essay-card {
    background: var(--linen-card, #fafaf7);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule-border, #e5e7eb);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--old-gold, #8b7355);
    border-radius: 4px;
    padding: 1.5rem 1.5rem 1.25rem;
    margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }
  .card-kicker {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--old-gold, #8b7355);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }
  .card-title {
    font-family: var(--font-serif, Georgia, serif);
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--deep-navy, #1e3a5f);
    line-height: 1.35;
    margin: 0 0 0.4rem;
  }
  .card-title a {
    color: var(--deep-navy, #1e3a5f);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .card-title a:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
  .card-byline {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: #475569;
    margin: 0 0 0.35rem;
  }
  .card-blurb {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: #334155;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
  }
  .card-cta {
    align-self: flex-start;
    color: #1d4ed8;
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 2px;
  }
  .card-cta:hover {
    color: #1e40af;
  }
  .card-cta-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.25rem 1.5rem;
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }
  .card-cta-row .card-cta {
    align-self: auto;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .card-status {
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--ink-soft, #475569);
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }
  .card-bridge {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: #64748b;
    font-style: italic;
    margin: 0.25rem 0 0;
  }
  .card-bridge a {
    color: #475569;
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
  .section-intro {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: #334155;
    margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
    max-width: 60ch;
  }
</style>
